video_description: Former President Trump on Thursday called Judge Juan Merchan “corrupt” after he was found guilty by a jury on 34 counts of falsifying business records in the first degree, stemming from a hush money payment made in the waning days of the 2016 election.   “This was a disgrace. This was a rigged trial by a conflicted judge who was corrupt,” Mr. Trump told reporters after leaving the courtroom. “The real verdict is going to be Nov. 5, by the people,” he said, referring to Election Day. “We didn’t do a thing wrong. I’m a very innocent man.”   He also falsely blamed President Biden. The case was brought by the state of New York and has nothing to do with the federal government.   Judge Merchan will sentence Mr. Trump on July 11, four days before the Republican National Convention.   Each count carries the possibility of up to four years in prison, but the judge is likely to impose the punishment concurrently.   The judge could also opt to impose a sentence of probation, with no prison time, or he could impose a fine or community service.   Mr. Trump is expected to appeal the decision, a process that could take months to years.   It’s one of four criminal cases involving the former president, but the others are not expected to go to trial before the November election.   Being a convicted felon does not prohibit Mr. Trump from seeking the presidency.   #donaldtrump #trump #hushmoney #cspan
